![Image](https://cdn.mos.cms.futurecdn.net/v6uqLtsafsLcTjhrLuj2ek.jpg)

![Image](https://www.esa.int/var/esa/storage/images/esa_multimedia/images/2005/01/wavelike_patterns_in_the_cloud_bands_of_saturn_s_atmosphere/10070280-2-eng-GB/Wavelike_patterns_in_the_cloud_bands_of_Saturn_s_atmosphere_pillars.jpg)

If there were a cosmic ocean large enough, **Saturn could float**.
With an average density of **0.69 g/cm³**, lower than water, Saturn stands out as the **least dense planet** in our solar system.

But this isn’t just a fun fact—it reveals something deeper. Saturn is composed mostly of **hydrogen and helium**, making it a **gas giant with no solid surface**. Despite its massive size, its internal structure is dominated by light elements, giving it this surprisingly low density.

👉 **Insight:**
Density plays a key role in understanding **planet formation, structure, and atmospheric behavior**.

